  "id": "019d2eae-c750-7033-b9ca-8d60ffe2e3c1",
  "content": "# ArcSwap HNSW Migration — Decision Record (2026-03-27)\n\n## What\nReplaced `Arc<Mutex<Hnsw>>` with `Arc<ArcSwap<Hnsw>>` in LiteStore for lock-free HNSW reads. PR #30, closes #17.\n\n## Key Design Decisions\n\n1. **ArcSwap<Hnsw> not ArcSwap<Arc<Hnsw>>**: `ArcSwap<T>` stores `Arc<T>` internally via `from_pointee`. No double-Arc needed.\n\n2. **True blue-green rebuild**: `rebuild_from_files()` builds the full new index before swapping. Searches continue using the old index throughout. Critical for runtime rebuilds (not just startup).\n\n3. **`index_entry_into()` refactor**: Extracted to accept a target HNSW reference. `index_entry()` calls it with `self.hnsw.load()`. `rebuild_from_files()` calls it with a local new_hnsw. This enables true blue-green without duplicating Redb metadata logic.\n\n4. **`flush_hnsw` uses `load_full()`**: Clones the Arc and releases the ArcSwap slot immediately, so a concurrent swap is not blocked during long file_dump I/O.\n\n5. **`std::thread::spawn` for deferred drop**: Used instead of `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` to be runtime-agnostic (rebuild_from_files is a sync fn).\n\n6. **Unsafe transmute unchanged**: The lifetime erasure on Hnsw happens before wrapping in ArcSwap. Safety argument is container-independent.\n\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering\n- ArcSwap `load()` returns a Guard that pins the old Arc. For short ops (search, insert) this is fine. For long ops (flush), use `load_full()` to avoid pinning.\n- When converting Mutex to ArcSwap, ordering of counter resets and swaps matters — operations that were atomic under Mutex become non-atomic and need explicit sequencing.",
